05050nam a22008055i 9780674294691DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742946917 a10.4159/97806742946912doi  a(DE-B1597)664985  a(OCoLC)1411307642  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHV875.5b.N65 2024 7aHIS0070002bisacsh04a362.734097281223/eng/202306011 aNolan, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUntil I Find You :bDisappeared Children and Coercive Adoptions in Guatemala /cRachel Nolan. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Lie We Love -- t2 Social Reports -- t3 Privatizing Adoptions -- t4 Adoption Rings and Baby Brokers -- t5 Children for Export -- t6 Disappeared Children -- t7 Best Interests of the Child -- t8 Inside Private Adoptions -- t9 The Reckoning -- tEpilogue: The Search -- tArchives and Interviews -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe poignant saga of Guatemala’s adoption industry: an international marketplace for children, built on a foundation of inequality, war, and Indigenous dispossession.In 2009 Dolores Preat went to a small Maya town in Guatemala to find her birth mother. At the address retrieved from her adoption file, she was told that her supposed mother, one Rosario Colop Chim, never gave up a child for adoption—but in 1984 a girl across the street was abducted. At that house, Preat met a woman who strongly resembled her. Colop Chim, it turned out, was not Preat’s mother at all, but a jaladora—a baby broker.Some 40,000 children, many Indigenous, were kidnapped or otherwise coercively parted from families scarred by Guatemala’s civil war or made desperate by unrelenting poverty. Amid the US-backed army’s genocide against Indigenous Maya, children were wrested from their villages and put up for adoption illegally, mostly in the United States. During the war’s second decade, adoption was privatized, overseen by lawyers who made good money matching children to overseas families. Private adoptions skyrocketed to the point where tiny Guatemala overtook giants like China and Russia as a “sender” state. Drawing on government archives, oral histories, and a rare cache of adoption files opened briefly for war crimes investigations, Rachel Nolan explores the human toll of an international industry that thrives on exploitation.Would-be parents in rich countries have fostered a commercial market for children from poor countries, with Guatemala becoming the most extreme case. Until I Find You reckons with the hard truths of a practice that builds loving families in the Global North out of economic exploitation, endemic violence, and dislocation in the Global South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdoption agencieszGuatemala. 0aAdoptionxCorrupt practiceszGuatemala. 0aDisappeared personszGuatemala. 0aIndian childrenzGuatemala. 0aIntercountry adoptionzGuatemala. 0aInterracial adoptionzGuatemala. 0aWrongful adoptionzGuatemala. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Central America.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aCongress.  aUS Latin American relations.  aabduction.  aadoptee.  aadoptive father.  aassault.  aassimilation.  abusiness.  adiplomacy.  aearthquake.  aethnicity.  aexport.  agender.  amass migration.  aorphans.  apostwar.  aseparated.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074971740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674294691?locatt=mode:legacy4